### What are Isolates?

Isolates are independent workers that run in parallel. Each isolate has its own memory heap and event loop. They communicate via message passing.

```dart
import 'dart:isolate';

void main() async {
  // ReceivePort to receive messages from the isolate
  var receivePort = ReceivePort();

  // Spawn an isolate
  await Isolate.spawn(worker, receivePort.sendPort);

  // Receive message
  var message = await receivePort.first;
  print('Received: $message');
}

void worker(SendPort sendPort) {
  sendPort.send('Hello from isolate!');
}
```

### Sending Data Back and Forth

```dart
import 'dart:isolate';

void main() async {
  var receivePort = ReceivePort();
  await Isolate.spawn(computeHeavy, receivePort.sendPort);

  var sendPort = await receivePort.first as SendPort;
  var resultPort = ReceivePort();

  sendPort.send({'value': 42, 'sendPort': resultPort.sendPort});
  var result = await resultPort.first;
  print('Result: $result');
}

void computeHeavy(SendPort sendPort) {
  var receivePort = ReceivePort();
  sendPort.send(receivePort.sendPort);

  receivePort.listen((message) {
    var data = message as Map;
    var input = data['value'] as int;
    var replyPort = data['sendPort'] as SendPort;

    // Heavy computation
    var result = input * input;
    replyPort.send(result);
  });
}
```

### Compute (Flutter)

```dart
import 'dart:async';

// Simulates Flutter's compute function
Future<R> compute<R, P>(FutureOr<R> Function(P) fn, P param) async {
  // In Flutter, this runs the function in a separate isolate
  return fn(param);
}

int heavyCalculation(int value) {
  var sum = 0;
  for (var i = 0; i < value; i++) {
    sum += i;
  }
  return sum;
}

void main() async {
  var result = await compute(heavyCalculation, 1000000);
  print('Result: $result');
}
```

| Aspect | Main Isolate | Worker Isolate |
|--------|-------------|----------------|
| Memory | Own heap | Own heap |
| Blocking | Blocks UI | Non-blocking |
| Communication | SendPort/ReceivePort | SendPort/ReceivePort |
| Use case | UI/light work | Heavy computation |

### Limitations

```dart
// What CANNOT be sent between isolates:
// - Mutable objects with native resources
// - Functions (closures)
// - Objects with native fields

// What CAN be sent:
// - Primitive types (int, double, bool, String, null)
// - Lists, Maps, Sets of sendable types
// - SendPort/ReceivePort
// - TypedData (ByteData, etc.)
```

> **Key Point:** Isolates provide true parallelism in Dart. Use them for CPU-intensive work to avoid blocking the UI thread. In Flutter, the `compute()` function simplifies isolate usage.

codeExample:
import 'dart:isolate';

int fibonacci(int n) {
  if (n <= 1) return n;
  return fibonacci(n - 1) + fibonacci(n - 2);
}

void fibonacciWorker(SendPort sendPort) {
  var receivePort = ReceivePort();
  sendPort.send(receivePort.sendPort);

  receivePort.listen((message) {
    var n = message as int;
    var result = fibonacci(n);
    sendPort.send(result);
  });
}

void main() async {
  var receivePort = ReceivePort();
  await Isolate.spawn(fibonacciWorker, receivePort.sendPort);

  var workerPort = await receivePort.first as SendPort;
  var resultPort = ReceivePort();

  workerPort.send(40);
  var result = await resultPort.first;
  print('Fibonacci(40) = $result');
}
